# Versioning and Conventional Commits

App version is **automated**: [semantic-release](https://github.com/semantic-release/semantic-release) runs on push to `main`, reads commit messages since the last tag, and bumps `package.json` version (no npm publish). The front end shows this version (see EMA-10). Netlify builds the commit that contains the bump, so production always has a clear version.

## Commit message format (Conventional Commits)

Write commit messages so the release bot can choose the bump type:

| Prefix / content | Bump type | Example |
|------------------|-----------|---------|
| `fix:` or `fix(scope):` | **PATCH** (0.1.0 â†’ 0.1.1) | `fix: date picker overlap on mobile` |
| `feat:` or `feat(scope):` | **MINOR** (0.1.1 â†’ 0.2.0) | `feat: display app version in header` |
| `BREAKING CHANGE:` in body, or `feat!:` / `fix!:` | **MAJOR** (0.2.0 â†’ 1.0.0) | `feat!: require org slug on signup` |

### CRITICAL â€” case-sensitive, exact format required

- Prefixes **MUST be lowercase**: `fix:` not `Fix:`, `feat:` not `Feat:` or `Feature:`.
- There **MUST be a colon** immediately after the type (or scope): `feat: add X` not `feat add X`.
- Use present tense, lowercase after the colon: `fix: resolve overlap` not `Fixed overlap`.
- Optional scope in parentheses: `feat(contracts): add template picker`.

### Common mistakes that **will not** trigger a release

| Wrong | Why it fails | Correct |
|-------|-------------|---------|
| `Fix: resolve overlap` | Capital `F` | `fix: resolve overlap` |
| `Feature: add templates` | `Feature` is not a type | `feat: add templates` |
| `Implement new dashboard` | No prefix at all | `feat: implement new dashboard` |
| `Refactor camera logic` | `Refactor` is not a prefix | `refactor: simplify camera logic` (no release) |

### Non-release prefixes (for clarity only)

Other prefixes (`chore:`, `docs:`, `refactor:`, `style:`, `test:`, `ci:`) do **not** trigger a release by default. Only `fix:` and `feat:` (and breaking changes) produce a version bump. Use the non-release prefixes for clarity â€” they still must be lowercase.

## When the version changes

- **When:** On **push to `main`**. If there are releasable commits (at least one `fix:` or `feat:` since last tag), the GitHub Action runs semantic-release, which updates `package.json`, commits, and creates a git tag (e.g. `v0.1.1`). Netlify then builds that commit, so the deployed app shows the new version.
- **No releasable commits:** semantic-release does nothing; no new tag or commit. So not every merge to main produces a new versionâ€”only when there are fix/feat commits.

